dict.string: Select this setting to prevent stacker wheel marks on some photographic papers. When reaching the printer, your job will be put on hold, to be printed from the printer's front panel with the stacker cover open.
Select this option to adjust for differences in black color values when converting colors between color spaces.
Indicates how to manage the colors that are out of range when converting between color spaces.
Use for presentation graphics, charts, or images that contain bright, saturated colors.
Use when you need to match a particular color and to print it accurately. This option also maps the white of the input space to the white of the paper on which the print job is printed.
Use when you need to print a draft to use for proofing. This option matches a particular color like the Relative Colorimetric option, but does not map the white.
Use for photographs or images in which colors blend together. The overall appearance of colors is preserved as much as possible.
Print your document reversed left-to-right.
Select this feature to permit the image or document to be automatically rotated in order to save paper or avoid clipping.
Prints your document on a paper size other than the one for which it is formatted.
Select to rotate the printed image or document by 90 degrees. If you are using roll paper, this feature can help reduce the amount of paper that is used for the print job.

Enter the job's Account ID. For printers where the "Request Account ID" feature exists and is enabled, the Account ID is provided by the printer administrator. In that case, if the printer has a queue, a job that does not have an Account ID may be put on hold and stored in the printer queue until an ID is entered from the Embedded Web Server.

The printable area is equal to the selected paper size. The printer will align the selected paper to the edge of the loaded paper. The printer will cut the paper with a size equal to the selected paper size. To avoid white areas in the border of the drawing caused by possible paper alignment problems, the contents of the drawing will be slightly magnified.

The printable area is equal to the selected paper size. The printer will align the selected paper size to the edge of the loaded paper and will clip the contents according to the selected margins. The printer will cut a paper with a size equal to the selected paper size. The printer will not print any data inside the clipped area.

The printable area is equal to the selected paper size. The printer will align the selected paper to the edge of the loaded paper. To avoid white areas in the border of the drawing caused by possible paper alignment problems, the printer will cut the paper with a size slightly smaller than the selected paper size.

The printable area is equal to the selected paper size. The printer will add the selected margins to the printable area and align the resulting paper to the edge of the loaded paper. The printer will cut the paper with a size equal to the selected paper size plus the selected margins.

The printable area is equal to the selected paper size minus the selected margins. The printer will add the selected margins to the printable area and align the resulting paper to the edge of the loaded paper. The printer will cut the paper with a size equal to the selected paper size.
This slider adjusts the amount of ink used to print your pages. The center position is the optimum for most users.
